# 18-07-2022 Class Notes

- <mark class="Aqua">Gentrification</mark> an be an issue for suburban neighbourhoods where they may feel encroached by construction companies and businesses that intend on using that part of the city for their own development.
	- Every developing country is seeing a rapid rate of <mark class="Yellow">urbanization</mark>, including India.
	- Many cities such as Bangalore, Mumbai and Delhi are being forced to expand beyond their capacity.
	-  Gentrification has "positive" impacts on the upper middle class but negative impacts on the less-economically developed neighbourhoods. 
	- "Gentrification is defined as the arrival of wealthier people in an existing urban area which increases property value and rent, and often changes the district character and culture"
		- → Not the same as urbanization
	- Urban renewal is not the same as gentrification; even though they can go hand in hand, it involves <mark class="Yellow">renewal and improvement</mark> not replacement.
- Urbanization → Urban Renewal → Gentrification 
- Rural → Urban migration occurs due to
	- Lack of more 'modern' job opportunities
	- Better education facilities like universities
	- Requiring better infrastructure like healthcare facilities. 

- Components that determine the creation of an urban settlement
	- Topology
	- Access to water and other resources
	- Weather
	- Trade routes → rivers, oceans, etc
	- Religious reasons(?) e.g. Ayodhya

# Bhutan vs Venezuela 
### Venezuela
- Venezuela has a staggering 88.28% urbanization rate (Statista, 2020) and 
- Venezuela has a population of 28.44 million and is expected to reach 35.57 million in upcoming decades.
- However, the current population growth is in negatives due to mass negative net migration. Since 2014, 7% of Venezuela's population has left the country, with 354 migrations per day.
- 
- While Venezuela is a 'petrostate', due to a lack of maintenance and labour, production rates and output is lower.
- Due to an ongoing humanitarian crisis, living in rural areas is difficult, while urban areas remain with poor infrastructure. Political corruption, chronic shortages of food and medicine, unemployment and closure of businesses, deterioration of productivity, economic mismanagement and overdependence on oil has led to a majority of the population being confined to overcrowded and underfunded urban areas.
